                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d93">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">751G.94/17: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Murphy</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Vichy</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-08-07T22:00:00+02:00"
                            >August 7, 1940—10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received August 7—12:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>278. Chauvel tells me this evening that the Gaimusho<note n="19" xml:id="d93fn19"
                        >The Japanese Foreign Office.</note> has now taken great pains to explain to
                    Arsene-Henry that the Japanese communication regarding Indochina should by no
                    means be construed as an ultimatum. The Foreign Office is advising Saint-Quentin
                    that the Japanese have expressed the desire to enter into negotiations regarding
                    the matter and have assured the French Government of their wish to avoid a
                        conflict.<note n="20" xml:id="d93fn20">On August 8 the French Counselor of
                        Embassy made similar statements to the Chief of the Division of Far Eastern
                        Affairs (751G.94/41).</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Murphy</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
